               <interp inst="t18261026-217" type="year" value="1826"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18261026-217" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18261026"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18261026-217" type="date" value="18261026"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18261026-217-off1198-c1282" targOrder="Y" targets="t18261026-217-defend1283 t18261026-217-off1198 t18261026-217-verdict1200"></join>
         
               <p>2008. 
               <persName id="t18261026-217-defend1283" type="defendantName">
                  MARTHA 
                  BYATT
               <interp inst="t18261026-217-defend1283" type="surname" value="BYATT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-defend1283" type="given" value="MARTHA"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-defend1283" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
             was indicted for <rs id="t18261026-217-off1198" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-off1198" type="offenceCategory" value="royalOffences"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-off1198" type="offenceSubcategory" value="coiningOffences"></interp>
               that she, on the <rs id="t18261026-217-cd1199" type="crimeDate">30th of September</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18261026-217-off1198 t18261026-217-cd1199"></join>, at St. George, Hanover-square, 12 pieces of false and counterfeit milled money and coin, each and every of them made and counterfeited to the likeness and similitude of a piece of good, lawful, and current milled money and silver coin of the realm, called a shilling; the same counterfeited and milled money, nor either of them not being then cut in pieces, unlawfully and feloniously did put off to one George Dutton at a lower rate and value than they by their denomination did import and were counterfeited for, that is to say, for the sum of 4s., against the statute
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>2d COUNT, the same, only stating that the said counterfeited pieces of milled money were put off at a lower rate, &amp;c. that is to say, for four pieces of the current coin of this realm, called shillings, of the value of 1s. each, against the statute.</p>
               <p>MR. BOLLAND conducted the prosecution.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18261026-217-person1284">
                  GEORGE 
                  DUTTON
               <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1284" type="surname" value="DUTTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1284" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1284" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I have known the prisoner from my childhood - eighteen years - in consequence of a communication from Limbrick, I had some interview with her, and agreed for her to meet me, on the 30th of September, at the Green Man public-house, Green-street, Grosvenor-square - she came - I saw her three or four doors from the house - I went in, and asked for a glass of cold gin and water - I then saw her come up to the house, and told Limbrick she was at the door; Lee then searched me in Limbrick's presence; I had nothing about me; Lee then gave me four shillings, which Limbrick marked - I put them into my pocket; I went to the prisoner, and asked if she had any little ones, meaning sixpences - I then said I wanted two dozen big ones, meaning shillings - she said, "You are<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182610260103"></xptr>going to break me at once" - I said, "No; I mean one dozen of big ones;" which she gave me; I put them into my pocket, and gave her the four shillings, which I had in my pocket - I went in, and in a few minutes, she was brought into the parlour and searched; I was also searched.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Q. Did I agreed to meet you that night? A. Your daughter did; you had agreed to meet me on the 25th of September, but did not come; and your daughter agreed for you to meet me on the 30th.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18261026-217-person1285">
                  JOHN 
                  LIMBRICK
               <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1285" type="surname" value="LIMBRICK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1285" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1285" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer of Hatton-garden. In consequence of information, which I received about the prisoner, I gave directions to Dutton; Lee and Kirby were in company with me. On the 30th of September, about a quarter to nine o'clock at night, at the Green Man; Dutton came into the house, and said, "They are in sight" - Lee then searched him - he had nothing about him; Lee gave him four shillings, which I had marked - he went out, and soon after returned. saying, "It is all right;" I then saw the prisoner brought in - she was searched, and the four marked shillings, which had been given to Dutton, were found on her - I searched Dutton, and found these twelve counterfeit shillings on him (producing them) - he said in her presence, that he got them from her; she exclaimed, "Oh! you traitor! Oh! Mr. Limbrick, I am a dead woman."</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18261026-217-person1286">
                  WILLIAM 
                  LEE
               <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1286" type="surname" value="LEE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1286" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1286" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was with Limbrick on this evening; he gave me four marked shillings, which I gave Dutton, after seeing that he had nothing about him - I went out shortly after him, and saw the prisoner near him - I took her, brought her in, and I found on her the four shillings, which I had given to Dutton; twelve shillings were found on him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18261026-217-person1287">
                  WILLIAM 
                  KIRBY
               <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1287" type="surname" value="KIRBY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1287" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1287" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I have heard the officer's evidence - it is correct.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18261026-217-person1288">
                  JOSEPH 
                  NICHOL
               <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1288" type="surname" value="NICHOL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1288" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1288" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am moneyer of the Mint. These shillings are counterfeit, and from one die - they do not appear to have been in circulation, but they have been prepared for circulation.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18261026-217-person1289">
                  JOHN 
                  FIELD
               <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1289" type="surname" value="FIELD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1289" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1289" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an inspector of counterfeit coin. - The shillings are counterfeit - they have been rubbed down with scowering-paper, and then coloured with something, to make them look black, as if they had been in circulation.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I have had twelve children - my husband is a painter and glazier, but neglected his business; I have been left in distress, and for a week together have been without a bit of meat; I have been brought to this through a person who owed me some rent, and gave me seven score of these - I kept them by me a long time, and wanted bread while I had them. I have often returned, after going out to pass them, and pawned something instead; it was nothing but distress led me to do it.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18261026-217-verdict1200" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-verdict1200" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>The prisoner was called upon to receive judgment, and upon praying benefit of clergy, a counter-plea was put in, on behalf of the Crown, and a record of the conviction of 
               <persName id="t18261026-217-person1290">
                  Martha 
                  Byatt
               <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1290" type="surname" value="Byatt"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1290" type="given" value="Martha"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1290" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
             read, for having put off, on the 25th of February, 1819, seven counterfeit shillings, to Cecilia Willis, for 2s. 71/2d. - the prisoner pleaded that she was not the same person, upon which a Jury were impannelled to try the issue.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18261026-217-person1291">
                  CALEB 
                  EDWARD POWELL
               <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1291" type="surname" value="EDWARD POWELL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1291" type="given" value="CALEB"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1291" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am assistant to the solicitor of the Mint. I produce a copy of the record of the conviction of Martha Byatt, at the April Session, 1819; I examined it with the original - it is correct - (read).</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18261026-217-person1292">
                  BARNARD 
                  GLEED
               <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1292" type="surname" value="GLEED"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1292" type="given" value="BARNARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1292" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I know the prisoner, and knew her in 1819 - I was present at the April Session that year; the prisoner is the person who was tried and convicted here - I was a witness on that occasion, and gave evidence against her.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18261026-217-person1293">
                  GEORGE 
                  BRAND
               <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1293" type="surname" value="BRAND"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1293" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-person1293" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was a turnkey at the House of Correction in 1819; the prisoner was in my custody twelve months from that time - I am certain of her person.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18261026-217-punish1201" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18261026-217-punish1201" type="punishmentCategory" value="death"></interp>
                     <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="t18261026-217-defend1283 t18261026-217-punish1201"></join>
               The Jury found that she was the same person, and she accordingly received sentence of Death
            </rs>.</p>
